<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrella throws seven-inning perfect game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) - Syracuse's Leo Estrella threw a seven-inning
perfect game against Indianapolis on Saturday night in his Triple-A
debut.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second perfect game in the International League this
season and 13th in the 117-year history of the league.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, Pawtucket's Tomo Ohka became the third pitcher in the
117-year history of the league to throw a nine-inning perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   Estrella, 25, needed just 64 pitches to retire the 21 batters in
the 5-0 victory. He struck out five, including the final two
batters of the game.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one hard hit ball in the game. With two outs in
the third inning, third baseman Ryan Freel made a diving catch of
Chad Green's line drive.
</P>
<P>
   Estrella went 5-5 with a 3.67 ERA at Tennessee, Toronto's
Double-A affiliate, before being promoted to Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   Estrella, 25, signed with the New York Mets in 1993 as an
undrafted free agent. He was traded to Toronto in 1998 for Tony
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   He went 14-7 with a 3.21 ERA last year at Class-A Dunedin.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribe fought back by winning the second game in the double
header 5-4, scoring 5 runs in the third inning off of three hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians and the SkyChiefs continue their four-game series on
Sunday at Victory Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
