<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Die in Texas Car Accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAN HORN, Texas (AP) -- A car going the wrong way on a Texas
interstate collided head-on with another car, killing all seven
people in the two vehicles, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Public Safety said a 1998 Pontiac was
traveling westbound in the eastbound lanes of the Interstate 10,
into the path of a tractor-trailer and a 1994 Nissan that was
trying to pass the big rig.
</P>
<P>
   Public safety spokesman Mike Cox said the truck veered to the
shoulder to avoid the Pontiac, which then collided with the Nissan,
sending both cars spinning in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the Pontiac was identified as Lorenzo Sukis, 33,
of El Paso. Also in the vehicle were Ivana Sukis, 10, and Pablo
Sukis, 5.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in the Nissan were Fredo Fernandez, 46, and Maria
Escobar, 51, both of Los Angeles; Carlos Laugart, 45, of South
Gate, Calif.; and an unidentified Hispanic woman.
</P>
<P>
   All were wearing seat belts except for the 5-year-old victim,
who was thrown from the Pontiac, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred around 2 p.m. Cox said the weather was dry
and clear and troopers found evidence that drinking may have been
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Only a grassy median separates the eastbound and westbound lanes
of the four-lane highway, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Public Safety originally said they thought the
tractor-trailer was towing the Nissan, which was clipped as the
Pontiac tried to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn is about 120 miles east of El Paso.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
