<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officer Killed in Sri Lanka Blast  </HEADLINE>
By DILIP GANGULY
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A bomb exploded in a relatively
peaceful region in eastern Sri Lanka on Sunday killing a local
police chief and wounding two others, a police official said.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb was apparently planted on a roadside in the Ampara
district and was set off by remote control as the police chief
walked by, a police official in the region said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   There was no claim of responsibility for the attack, but police
blamed it on Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Ampara has long been relatively free from the separatist
campaign launched by the Tamil guerrillas, which is centered in the
northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam has fought Sri Lankan
government forces for 17 years to carve out a separate homeland for
the Tamils, a minority in Sinhala-dominated Sri Lanka. More than
62,000 people have been killed in the insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   In a shift in policy on Sunday, the Tigers appealed to Sri
Lanka's Muslim minority to help them in their struggle for a
homeland -- despite past Tiger violence against Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tamil Eelam belongs to the Muslim and Tamil people,'' the
rebels said in a statement. ''We urge your cooperation in working
toward strengthening the Tamil-Muslim relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamils, who form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 18.6 million people,
are mostly Hindus. Muslims, who share the same language as Tamils,
make up 7.1 percent of the population. The rest of the population
is Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Tamil Tigers have forced tens of thousands of
Muslims out of their homes in the northern Jaffna peninsula, and in
1990 guerrillas killed 205 Muslims in two separate massacres.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what prompted the rebels to issue
the appeal to win over the Muslims. The rebels, after a string of
military success, have faced stiff military resistance in the north
during the past four weeks after coming close to their former
capital of Jaffna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-18-00 0531 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000618.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 05:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan PM Seeks Public Spending Boost  </HEADLINE>
By GARY SCHAEFER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A week ahead of parliamentary elections, Japan's
Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori said Sunday that more injections of
public spending are likely in a bid to boost the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Mori said his administration plans to continue spending
aggressively until Japan recovers from its deepest slump in decades
-- a policy inherited from former Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who
died of a stroke last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until there are signs of a more stable recovery, I plan to
follow the pace set by Mr. Obuchi,'' Mori said in an interview on
TV Asahi.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister said he had told government officials to
prepare to compile a second budget for the fiscal year to pay for
more public works projects.
</P>
<P>
   The government announced earlier this month that the economy
grew in fiscal 1999 after two years of contractions, expanding a
modest 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Inflated by government spending on construction and other
projects, gross domestic product grew 2.4 percent between January
and March, its fastest quarterly expansion in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Convincing voters he can keep up that momentum is one of Mori's
most urgent tasks as Japan prepares to go to the polls June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that Mori's Liberal Democratic Party, which has
governed Japan almost without interruption for the last 45 years,
and its two coalition partners may struggle to secure a comfortable
majority in the ballot for the lower house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Japanese opposition parties and some economists argue
that Mori's prescription for the economy will leave the nation with
a crippling debt burden.
</P>
<P>
   Yukio Hatoyama, the leader of the largest opposition Democratic
Party, chastised Mori for his ''bankrupt fiscal policy'' on TV
Asahi.
</P>
<P>
   ''If economic recovery was simply a matter of spending a lot of
money on public-works projects, the economy should have gotten
better by now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
