<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Rebels Stage Night Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Chechen rebels staged overnight
hit-and-run attacks on Russian police stations in the capital
Grozny and three Russian-held regions, officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian artillery and warplanes on Sunday continued to bombard
Chechen fighters' refuges in the southern mountains and in the key
Argun gorge near the border with Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Two temporary police stations in Grozny and four police
checkpoints in the Nozhai-Yurt, Shelkovskaya and Urus-Martan
districts were fired on overnight, a spokesman for the regional
Russian Interior Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the police did not suffer any casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Russian warplanes and artillery bombed mountain passes in the
Argun gorge near the Georgian border, aiming at suspected
concentrations of Chechen insurgents, the North Caucasus military
command's press service said.
</P>
<P>
   The Argun gorge is a key rebel refuge and supply route to
Georgia, the only foreign country bordering Chechnya. Russian
forces are trying to wipe out guerrilla bands hiding in the
mountains, using their massive advantage in firepower while
avoiding close combat.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Sharo-Argun, deep in the mountains, federal
troops carrying out a special operation found a rebel weapons cache
with 65 artillery shells, the command's press center said.
</P>
<P>
   As police swept the village searching for rebels, they seized
from the local population 42 firearms, 10,000 cartridges, 264
artillery shells, five grenade launchers and 88 pounds of dynamite,
the center's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Police detained 54 villagers for various violations.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighboring village of Dekhesty, troops unearthed a rebel
hide-out and found medicine, civilian clothing and military
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were expelled from Chechnya in a 1994-96 war with
independence fighters. They re-entered the republic after Islamic
militants based there seized several villages in the neighboring
Russian region of Dagestan, and after about 300 people died in
apartment bombings the government blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
