<HEADLINE> Hornsby fired as Yonkers schools superintendent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The city of Yonkers has fired its schools
superintendent after he battled the mayor's attempts to get the
city out from under a court order to desegregate its schools.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden firing Friday night of Andre J. Hornsby, the city's
first black superintendent, came just after he announced improved
test scores and the narrowing of a gap in achievement between black
and white students. He had served in the post since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby was pressuring Mayor John Spencer to provide more city
money to cover a deficit he estimated at $34 million. But the
dispute over money was inextricably tied to the fights over race
and schools in a city that has long been a prime battleground for
desegregation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court recently ruled that Yonkers, the state's
fourth-largest school district, was free of the vestiges of
segregation that prompted a 1986 desegregation order. Hornsby had
argued that remnants of racism remained in the system and that the
decision should be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Board members insisted they were not abandoning the goals of
desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby left the meeting Friday without comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
