<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 06:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Sign Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Ethiopia and Eritrea signed a cease-fire
agreement in their more than two-year-old border war on Sunday,
opening the way for negotiators to try to draw their bitterly
disputed frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The accord, however, does not bring a definitive end to the 25
months of fighting between the African neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The accord, reached under the auspices of the Organization of
African Unity, calls for international peacekeepers to deploy in a
''security zone'' while the negotiators are at work.
</P>
<P>
   Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, whose country currently
presidents over the OAU, saluted ''the efforts of the OAU, the
African capitals, the United States, the European Union and the
United Nations for (their work toward) increased stability and a
global peace in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia insists it will not withdraw its troops from Eritrean
territory it has seized in the fighting until U.N. peacekeepers are
deployed in a buffer zone along the border.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan sent officials to Africa to
discuss plans for peacekeepers. Some diplomats have suggested a
force of about 2,000 troops, but others have said nearly double
that many may be required.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of soldiers and civilians are believed to have
been killed and wounded since war broke out between the two Horn of
Africa countries in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest round of fighting, Ethiopian forces steamrolled
into Eritrea on May 12, capturing land for beyond the disputed
border regions. Eritrea accepted the OAU cease-fire plan in May.
While Ethiopia agreed to it in principle on June 10, fighting had
continued on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
