<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 06:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Rebels Ready To Negotiate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Southern Sudanese rebels said Sunday they
were willing to return to negotiations after the United States and
Kenya began a push for new peace talks to end Sudan's 17-year civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Sudan People's Liberation Army decided to end
their suspension of negotiation, a spokesman said. They had walked
out of on May 8 to protest government airplanes' bombing of
civilian targets in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel our conditions for suspension have been met,'' Samson
Kwaje, the SPLA spokesman said. He said British, U.S. and Canadian
pressure had brought an end to the attacks, adding that the SPLA
was ''willing to come back any time they fix a date.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a protracted series of peace talks was to have
begun May 17 in Nairobi. The talks are mediated by the regional
Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD), funded by a
group of Western donor, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Harry Johnston, the U.S. special envoy for Sudan, met
with Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi in Nairobi, and both agreed
to press for a resumption of talks, Moi's press service said.
</P>
<P>
   Kwaje also said five of 11 non-governmental aid agencies
operating in southern Sudan that had refused to accept rebel
conditions on delivering aid to the region would be allowed back in
after they agreed to sign a memorandum of understanding. He named
the agencies as Oxfam, CARE International, Save the Children-UK,
VSF-Germany and VSF-Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately possible to confirm the report with any
of the agencies on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2 million people have died, most of them in
war-related famines, since the civil war broke out in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who practice mainly Christianity or traditional
African religions, seek broad autonomy from the Arab, Muslim north.
</P>
<P>
   Sudanese President Omar el-Bashir and the rebels have agreed in
principle that there should be a referendum on self-determination
in what was defined as southern Sudan at the time of independence.
</P>
<P>
   But the SPLA has proposed that other areas, including the Nuba
Mountains, also be included in the vote, something the government
has rejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
