<DOCNO> APW20000618.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Prime Minister Appointed  </HEADLINE>
By SHAFIKA MATTAR
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- King Abdullah II accepted the resignation
Sunday of the government and appointed a new prime minister who is
known as a keen supporter of economic reforms, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Abu Ragheb, 54, will replace Prime Minister Abdur-Ra'uf
Rawabdeh, whose resignation had been widely expected following
criticism of him in parliament. A petition signed by lawmakers in
April had urged Abdullah to dismiss Rawabdeh's government for
failing to deliver on promised political and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ragheb was asked by the king to form a Cabinet, and he has
begun consultations with various officials and lawmakers, said the
official, speaking on condition of anonymity. Abu Ragheb is
expected to keep control the ministries of foreign affairs,
finance, trade and industry, tourism and labor.
</P>
<P>
   The new government will comprise economists and technically
oriented experts to face Jordan's ''economic challenges,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ragheb's pro-business attitude is expected to address
businessmen's displeasure with Jordan's strained ties with Iraq,
which has resulted in lower foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
   Very little is known about Abu Ragheb's views on Israel, with
which Jordan signed a peace treaty in 1994. Relations with Israel
are a sensitive issue in Jordan, where about 60 percent of its 5
million people are ethnic Palestinians. Abu Ragheb is of
Palestinian descent.
</P>
<P>
   The Amman-born Abu Ragheb graduated from Tennessee University in
the United States in 1967 with a degree in civil engineering. He
was industry and trade minister in 1991 and energy minister in
1995-1996. He was trade and industry minister again in 1996 and
1997.
</P>
<P>
   He did not hold any post in Rawabdeh's government. That
government was the first appointed by Abdullah after he ascended
the throne in February 1999 following the death of his father, King
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ragheb, who has been a lawmaker since 1993, was head of the
economic and financial committee in parliament and a member of the
Royal Economic Consultative Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-18-00 0902 </TRAILER>
