<DOCNO> APW20000618.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Horn of Africa Pact  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said the agreement by
Ethiopia and Eritrea to cease hostilities in their border war is a
''breakthrough'' and he hopes the two countries can ''realize their
potential in peace instead of squandering it in war.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord reached Sunday in Algeria after more than two weeks
of talks does not bring a definitive end to the 25 months of
fighting that has left thousands of dead in the Horn of Africa. It
does allow a reprieve while negotiators delineate the bitterly
disputed frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a breakthrough which can, and should end the tragic
conflict in the Horn of Africa,'' Clinton said in a statement
Sunday. ''It can, and should permit these two countries to realize
their potential in peace, instead of squandering it in war.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he hopes their agreement to end the fighting
''also signals their commitment to build the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia and Eritrea should use the next round of talks to
produce ''a final, comprehensive, lasting agreement, so they can
get on with the work of pursuing democracy and development for
their people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ethiopia and Eritrea are America's friends. If they are ready
to take the next step, we and our partners in the international
community will walk with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he has asked his special envoy to the talks, former
national security adviser Anthony Lake, to return to Algiers to
work with the Organization of African Unity, which mediated the
accord, on the next round of negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-18-00 0947 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000618.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Urged Vs. Assad Kin Permit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spanish police urged the government last
year to deny the exiled brother of Syria's late president Hafez
Assad a residency permit on grounds that his bodyguards were
troublemakers, but officials gave him one anyway, a newspaper said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The government ruled that Rifaat Assad had not done anything
wrong himself, and granted him a one-year permit that expires in
November, El Pais said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also said Spain's government was irked last week when
Rifaat, living in the resort town of Marbella, declared himself the
rightful heir to Syria's presidency following his brother's death
and said he would challenge Bashar Assad, Hafez's son and
hand-picked successor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not allow any foreigner residing in Spain to make
comments that might jeopardize the stability of a country with
which we maintain cordial relations,'' El Pais quoted a Foreign
Ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were not available Sunday to comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   Rifaat Assad, 63, has been living in Marbella off and on for
more than a decade, and is said to have several businesses and
extensive real estate holdings there.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has a diplomatic passport because technically he remained
Syria's vice president even though he had been exiled after trying
to overthrow his brother in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   When Hafez Assad stripped him of that post in 1998, the passport
became invalid and Rifaat had to apply for residency in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spanish police unit that handles visas and immigration
issues urged Madrid not to grant Assad a residency permit, citing a
number of violent incidents involving his bodyguards, El Pais said.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1990, Assad's head of security and three aides were
convicted of robbing a restaurant in Marbella. The judge said their
goal was to terrorize the owner into selling the restaurant to
Rifaat Assad.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1989, some of Assad's bodyguards pointed guns at
photographers trying to snap shots of Assad dining inside another
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, on September 2 of last year, six Syrians
including Assad's son Sirwan were arrested for hitting a policeman
during a scuffle. They also faced weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warning from police, Spain's Interior Ministry
granted Assad residency.
</P>
<P>
   All his papers were in order, he has financial means to support
himself and Assad himself had not run afoul of the law, a ministry
official speaking on condition of anonymity confirmed to The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Syria's ruling Baath Party opened its first
conference in 15 years to elect Bashar Assad party leader and
declare his candidacy for president, putting him closer to
succeeding his father. The gathering was held a week after Hafez
Assad, who took power in a 1970 coup, died of a heart attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-18-00 0951 </TRAILER>
