</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BAILEY, Colo. (AP) -- Government leaders are assessing damage to the
environment caused by two wildfires burning in the foothills of the Rocky
Mountains. The blazes have blackened 21,000 acres and destroyed 54 homes since
Monday. Rain and snow on the narrow mountain roads kept most firefighters from a
blaze east of Rocky Mountain National Park early yesterday. One crew spent the
night near the fire site, and officials said firefighters expect to have it
contained today. The second fire, about 35 miles southwest of Denver, is
expected to be contained by Wednesday.
</P>
