<HEADLINE> Albright Presses Lebanon Leader  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
pressed Lebanon on Sunday to accept the United Nations'
verification of Israel's troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Albright called Lebanese President Emile Lahoud several times
until about 4 a.m., said a statement issued by Lahoud's office.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon has refused to accept U.N. verification that Israel has
completely withdrawn from the country. Lebanon says Israel still
occupies pockets of its territory. On Sunday, Lebanese and U.N.
cartographers set out on foot to inspect some of the disputed
points.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Lahoud denied press reports that the
government had accepted the U. N. certification following his
telephone conversations with Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lebanon insisted that it will not give its consent before the
(Israeli) withdrawal is first verified by its team and the U.N.
team,'' the statement added.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon's rejection of the U.N. verification is a setback for
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who had hoped to discuss the
next steps to achieve peace in the Middle East during his trip to
the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lebanon will consider the Israeli withdrawal to be incomplete
if the Israeli violations on its internationally recognized border
are not eliminated. It will not accept a fictitious line as a
substitute for the international border,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is expected to dominate Annan's meetings with
Lebanese leaders in Beirut on Monday. It has also delayed the
deployment of U.N. peacekeeping forces to southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Israeli pullout May 24, Iranian-backed Hezbollah
guerrillas, who fought Israeli forces for 18 years, have moved into
the former occupied zone. On Saturday, Hezbollah warned it would
resume attacks on Israel's north if the Jewish state does not give
up tracts of land claimed by Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, Hezbollah's main backer, supported Lebanon's stand. Annan
and Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali held talks in Tehran, where
Annan stopped on his way to Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the U.N. Security Council reached a tentative
agreement to endorse the U.N. verification of the Israeli
withdrawal. The council held a marathon 10-hour session Saturday,
including a conference call with Lahoud, Albright and others, U.N.
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of the south in
1985 to establish a buffer against guerrilla attacks on northern
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Under 1978 Security Council resolutions, U.N. peacekeeping
troops were charged with verifying the Israeli pullout. They are
also required to help the Lebanese army -- when it is eventually
deployed -- restore security and authority in the border zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
