<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF Ends Ottey Drug Hearing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTE CARLO, Monaco (AP) -- Jamaican sprinter Merlene Ottey,
facing a two-year ban after testing positive for the steroid
nandrolone, will learn her fate later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio Reineri, spokesman for the International Amateur
Athletic Federation, said Sunday no decision was expected quickly
on her arbitration hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Ottey, a former world 200-meter champion and one of the most
decorated athletes in the sport, tested positive at a meet in
Switzerland in July 1999. She denied taking the drug and was
cleared by her national federation.
</P>
<P>
   The IAAF refused to accept the Jamaicans' ruling and sent her
case to its arbitration panel. Ottey appeared before the three-man
panel in a closed-door hearing Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Nandrolone is a steroid that is easily detectable in standard
drug tests. But there has been a spate of positive nandrolone cases
around the world over the past year, prompting speculation that the
drug is contained in nutritional supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ''The debate (in the hearing) focused on some scientific data,
the ability of the body to produce nandrolone and some legal
arguments,'' Reineri said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel chairman, Christoph Vedder of Germany, has said the
case could be an important test for sports law regarding
nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
   Ottey, winner of 34 individual medals in major international
championships, hopes to compete in the Sydney Olympics at 40.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the IAAF panel held a final hearing on Cuban high
jumper Javier Sotomayor's positive test for cocaine. That ruling
also is expected this week. Like Ottey, Sotomayor would face a
two-year suspension if found guilty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
