<HEADLINE> Docs Remove Iran Reformer's Bullet  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Doctors have removed a bullet from the neck
of a leading reformer who was shot and critically wounded last
March in an assassination attempt, a close aide said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Saeed Hajjarian was discharged from the hospital after the
surgery Saturday and has returned home, said the aide, who
identified himself only as Tajik.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet had been lodged close to his spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is improving day by day but still cannot make a speech. He
can talk in the form of short sentences,'' Tajik told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian, a city councilor and a close confident of reformist
President Mohammad Khatami, was shot in the head March 12. Saeed
Asghar, who police say fired the gun, was caught, tried and
sentenced to 15 years in jail. Four others received three to 10
year prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian, who is considered the architect of Khatami's popular
reform program, is widely believed to have been the victim of an
intense power struggle between Khatami's reformist allies and
hard-liners desperate to cling to power despite their unpopularity.
</P>
<P>
   Many reformers have criticized the trial of the alleged
attackers, saying the court made no effort to uncover the
masterminds behind the shooting. They have accused the hard-liners
of ordering the attack on Hajjarian.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian's paper, Sobh-e-Emrooz, was one of 18 reformist
newspapers that were shut down over the past two months as part of
an unprecedented media crackdown by the hard-line judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Tajik said Saeed Mortazavi, the judge in charge of the hard-line
press court, has summoned Hajjarian to court to answer
press-related charges against him but said Hajjarian would ignore
the call.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would certainly not attend the court because he is unable
to make a long speech,'' he said. He did not say when Hajjarian was
summoned to the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
