White Man To Be Tried in Bombing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A white man goes on trial tomorrow, charged with
setting off pipe bombs at mostly black Florida A&AMP;M University. The federal
charges, which include carrying out a hate crime, could get Lawrence Lombardi
life in prison if he's convicted. Although there were no injuries, news of the
threat spread fear across the predominantly black college campus. Lombardi has
maintained his innocence. The trial is being held in Pensacola out of concern
Lombardi might not get a fair trial in Tallahassee, A&AMP;M's home city.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll Finds Abortion Views Conflicted
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A majority of Americans believe abortion is murder, but
more than two-thirds think the decision to have one must be left to a woman and
her doctor, according to a Los Angeles Times poll released today. The poll is
full of responses that seem contradictory. Sixty-five percent of those
questioned oppose a constitutional amendment banning abortion but only 43
percent support the landmark Roe vs. Wade decision. A majority of those surveyed
think homosexuality is wrong, but sixty percent said they feel comfortable
around gays and lesbians. Only 40 percent felt that way in a 1983 poll.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Praises Horn of Africa Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today said the agreement by Ethiopia and
Eritrea to cease hostilities in their border war is a ''breakthrough'' and he
hopes the two countries can ''realize their potential in peace instead of
squandering it in war.'' ''This is a breakthrough which can, and should end the
tragic conflict in the Horn of Africa,'' Clinton said in a statement. The accord
reached today in Algeria does not bring a definitive end to the 25 months of
fighting. It does allow a reprieve while negotiators delineate the bitterly
disputed frontier.
</P>
