<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rules Aimed at Stormwater Runoff  </HEADLINE>
By LEON DROUIN KEITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Water quality officials want cleaner
California beaches to begin at home -- and at gas stations,
restaurants and ''big box'' stores.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed rules in the Los Angeles area could require owners of
many new and renovated structures in Southern California to take
measures to keep rainwater out of storm drains or treat the water
before it enters the system.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the state, the rules would apply to hillside
houses as well as developments of 10 homes or more. The rules could
affect thousands of developments a year, forcing improvements like
detention ponds that could add thousands of dollars to construction
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect has angered some residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't even imagine where I would put something like that,''
said James Martin, a retired university professor who owns a
two-bedroom hillside home in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
   Martin won't have to follow the rules because he doesn't intend
to make major changes to his property. But when he sells, he said,
he expects the buyers will follow the neighborhood trend and expand
the house, which is perched in the San Gabriel Mountains with views
of the Los Angeles basin.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all want as pure an ocean as we can, but this approach
seems extremely burdensome for the individual,'' Martin said,
adding that cities ought to handle the problem by building holding
ponds that can meet the cumulative needs of several properties.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 Santa Monica Bay study found that 4 percent of people who
swim within 100 yards of a storm drain will suffer at least one
symptom -- cough, ear ailment, sore throat, fever, chills or some
gastrointestinal disorder. The long-term effects of such exposure
have not been thoroughly studied.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, approved by the Los Angeles Regional Water Quality
Control Board, are intended to keep runoff tainted with gasoline,
motor oil, pesticides and human and animal waste from polluting
beaches. More than 30 Los Angeles-area communities are opposed. The
State Water Resources Control Board has final say, but no date had
been set for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Montevideo, a lawyer representing two builders' groups
and cities opposed to the rules, said his clients aren't against
cleaner oceans; they just want an approach that doesn't burden
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The rules require the diversion of three-quarters of an inch of
rainwater. Someone with an acre of paved property will have to
figure out what to do with 27,000 gallons of runoff, Montevideo
said. He added that a detention basin for an apartment complex
could wind up costing more than $8,000 a unit.
</P>
<P>
   Other estimates are lower. Dennis Dickinson, executive officer
of the Los Angeles water quality board, said the changes will add
about 1 percent to the cost of a development -- or $5,000 to a
$500,000 home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question is, are we going to leave a legacy to future
generations of inherently polluting design, or do we start dealing
with that now and trying to avoid it?'' Dickinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Some actually see savings in the rules, which could affect more
than 16,000 new homes a year in Venture and Los Angeles counties.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Cornet and her husband created a 69-acre development in
Davis, known as Village Homes, that allows rainwater to percolate
into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Narrow streets, graded land, channels and ponds encourage the
soil to absorb rainwater at the 220-house, 40-apartment
development. Its success has earned praise from groups as varied as
the Natural Resources Defense Council and the National Association
of Home Builders.
</P>
<P>
   The system cost $700 a unit less than conventional storm drain
systems and proved to be more effective when a flood hit after the
development was completed in 1981. Not only did the development not
flood when neighboring areas were inundated, it soaked in other
communities' runoff, she said. Cornet, now the executive director
of the nonprofit Local Government Commission in Davis, said Village
Homes' example has not drawn many imitators.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's tough to get developers and city planners to think of
doing anything other than what they've always done,'' she said.
''It must just be the fear of the unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules affect more than housing developments and
hillside homes. Also included are car repair shops, gas stations,
restaurants and parking lots with 25 or more spaces. Any
development next to or that discharges stormwater directly into
environmentally sensitive areas also would be subject to the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rules focus on new development, it will take a while
for them to significantly reduce coastal pollution, said Michael
Stenstrom, director of the University of California-Los Angeles'
Institute of the Environment. The changes, he said, are ''little
steps for little feet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
