<HEADLINE> Iran Reformers Urge Rights Respect  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran's new reformist legislature warned the
hard-line judiciary Sunday that its ''illegal behavior'' toward the
press has damaged the country's international image, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   A letter signed by 151 lawmakers called on the head of the
judiciary, Ayatollah Mahmoud Hashemi Shahroudi, to ''put an end to
illegal and politically motivated closure of newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, parliament agreed to discuss a bill to amend the
press law and lift press freedom restrictions imposed by their
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for introducing the bill, which was drawn
up last week. The bill will be the first legislative show of
commitment to change by the reformers, who swept the Feb. 18
elections and ousted hard-liners from parliament after 20 years of
control.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was the new parliament's first strong attack on the
judiciary, which has closed down 18 reformist publications, most of
them popular newspapers, over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers have promised to give priority to press and political
reforms in the new legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''Illegal behavior of the Tehran Justice Administration toward
the press has not only damaged the judiciary's credibility in the
eyes of the public, but it has also tarnished Iran's international
image,'' the official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted the
letter as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The letter also expressed ''deep concern'' over the detention of
individuals without meeting the legal requirements and called on
the judiciary to respect the legal rights of detainees.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-line judiciary has arrested and jailed several
pro-reform writers and political activists in the past two months
as part of an intense power struggle between reformers, supported
by President Mohammad Khatami, and hard-liners, favored by Supreme
Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are calling for fundamental reforms in the judiciary so
that the rights of suspects are respected and politically motivated
practices are not applied to individuals,'' lawmaker Ali-Reza Nouri
told The Associated Press on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just want the judiciary to fulfill its constitutional
responsibilities and respect the rights of citizens,'' said Nouri,
who signed the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the laws that have been in place since the 1979 Islamic
revolution are unpopular for restricting personal freedoms, and the
reformist victory in parliament has raised hopes that such laws
will be eased.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their majority in parliament, it will not be easy for
the reformers to get their way. Khamenei is the final authority in
Iran, and all bills passed by the legislature must be approved by
the Guardian Council, a hard-line watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   Since his 1997 election, Khatami has eased many social,
political and cultural restrictions that the clerical establishment
seeks to maintain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
