<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small city drops recycling, ruse of national commitment  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GORMLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, N.Y. (AP) - Deborah Cohen hates the high taxes she
pays on her hairdresser's wages. But when her city stood alone and
dropped its costly recycling program in defiance of a state
lawsuit, she knew something much more valuable was at stake: the
future of her 10-year-old daughter, India.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was shocked,'' Cohen said. ''I'm concerned for her future
and her environment.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Michael Jeffers, a college student, hiker and camper who
revels in nature, say they carefully separated and sorted bottles,
cans and newspapers, never suspecting their struggling Rust Belt
city would trash recycling.
</P>
<P>
   But what's happening in Amsterdam, N.Y., like the nation's
commitment to recycling, may be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   There have been rumblings for years against mandatory curbside
sorting from cash-strapped cities like this one to Los Angeles. The
reasons include rising costs while market prices drop and a growing
concern that recyclables are being dumped in landfills and
incinerators like trash. Yet Amsterdam is the first to drop the
effort that has changed the habits of most Americans since the
first Earth Day three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Amsterdam is the only municipality that turned its back on
recycling,'' said Marc Violette, spokesman for state Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer. That office is suing Amsterdam not to exact
fines, but to restore recycling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're dealing with the Amsterdam situation very seriously,''
Violette said ''We don't want other municipalities to violate the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not against recycling as long as it's recycling,''
countered Amsterdam Mayor John M. Duchessi Jr., a Democrat, former
VISTA volunteer and a lifetime firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that dropping the $180,000 recycling program
wasn't, as the state contends, to cut costs. Duchessi said the city
was simply admitting reality - that recyclables were being dumped
in a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ''People don't like to wash and sort their recyclables only to
see them dumped in the garbage truck,'' Duchessi said. ''My fear is
that people would develop a disdain for recycling.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a quiet landfilling of recyclable materials,'' said
Jerry Taylor, director of natural resource studies for the Cato
Institute, a Libertarian think tank in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''That problem has increased in recent years - reports of it,''
said Brian Taylor, editor of the industry magazine Recycling Today.
He said no one knows what part of recyclable material is
landfilled, but he believes it's a small percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Feldman of the Institute for Local Self-Reliance, a
Washington, D.C., think tank, said Los Angeles, Philadelphia,
Washington and other cities have seriously considered cutting back
recycling. Public backlashes, however, quickly restored them.
</P>
<P>
   Even the attorney general agrees recyclables are often carefully
cleaned, bundled and sorted only to be mixed with garbage. Spitzer
has introduced legislation that would change that.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are numerous complaints,'' said Spitzer spokesman
Violette. ''In many cases, those allegations are confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's office is investigating these allegations
statewide. A state survey found 68 percent of municipalities
received complaints that recyclables were trashed.
</P>
<P>
   So why don't more officials follow Amsterdam's lead?
</P>
<P>
   Most often the cost of recycling, which has broad public
support, is buried in municipal budgets, said Jerry Taylor of the
Cato Institute. ''You don't get much at the ballot box to say
you're dismantling recycling and it doesn't matter if it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Enck, an environmental director with the state Attorney
General's Office, said a resident called her office because he saw
the recycling hauler dump sorted material into the garbage truck.
He said he couldn't get his town supervisor or a state agency to
even a call the hauler.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear to us there's widespread public support (in
households) for recycling. It's just become second nature,'' she
said. ''We concede that communities often don't make money (from
recycling), but there are other economic benefits and, besides,
it's the law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the problems with this local government recycling
malaise is that in the early and mid-1990s there was a lot of money
for recycling,'' Enck said. But a demand for recycled paper and
cardboard in the Pacific has eased, and other prices have dropped.
</P>
<P>
   However, she insists that when governments consider the cost of
precious landfill space, recycling pays.
</P>
<P>
   State figures that show a steady rise in recycling, which Enck
said appears to be leveling off, are also suspect. When mandatory
recycling began in New York in 1988, local governments did most of
the collecting. Now the work is often contracted and those figures
can reflect what is left at the curbs, not what is left at
recycling plants for reuse. Recycling in New York increased from
claiming 3 percent of the waste stream in 1987 to 42 percent, which
would be one of the best marks nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are also disappointed with local government's
lax enforcement of recycling, either because of a lack of staffing
or because recyclables help meet the needs of an incinerator.
</P>
<P>
   In Amsterdam, the mayor insists his city's stand isn't about
money. He said he expects to reinstate recycling. But the city that
operates on a $17.05 million budget already rejected a low bid of
$188,000 in March. That would have cost each household $20 a year.
This month, city council tabled action on a bid because it was
$70,000 more than the city's $100,000 recycling budget. The
Attorney General's Office promptly filed suit after spending six
months to help the city return to recycling.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thrust really isn't financial,'' he said. ''It was that we
were wasting time and energy to recycle ... We're willing to spend
the money, but not to dump it in the landfill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
