<HEADLINE> Militaries Challenge Civilian Rule  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Army officers overthrow Ecuador's
elected government in South America's first successful coup in more
than a decade. Paraguayan troops fire at the legislative palace
with automatic weapons before surrendering amid a state of siege.
</P>
<P>
   In Peru, the armed forces are accused of intimidating opposition
candidates in the presidential election. And Venezuela's populist
president, who once led a failed coup, appoints generals to top
government posts and vastly increases the military's role in
society.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of widespread corruption, soaring crime and the
world's most unequal distribution of wealth, some Latin American
armies are flexing their muscles again amid a perceived failure by
civilian governments to provide justice and a decent quality of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Latin American militaries are stirring. Other countries
have continued a trend in the 1990s of moving away from the brutal
military dictatorships that dominated most of the last century.
Argentina and Chile, once home to some of the region's worst
military repression, appear to be keeping their armies safely in
check.
</P>
<P>
   But with military rumblings challenging the principle of
civilian rule in at least a half dozen countries, it's becoming
clear the region hasn't yet closed the darkest chapters of its
history.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Latin American landscape, the military is the
institution that people turn to because there is no other: Parties
have been discredited, congress doesn't work and there's widespread
corruption,'' said Michael Shifter, a Latin America specialist at
the Inter-American Dialogue think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that much of the concern about the military
is concentrated in the Andean region, which has been plagued by
economic slumps, drug-related corruption, electoral irregularities,
a backlash against free-market reforms and, in the case of
Colombia, a guerrilla insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   In Ecuador, military officers overthrew President Jamil Mahuad
in January before being pressured by the United States to return
power to the civilian vice president.
</P>
<P>
   A bitter election campaign in Venezuela is reportedly costing
President Hugo Chavez support in the military and stirring
speculation of a possible coup by officers opposed to Chavez's
perceived attempts to politicize the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Colombia, where the army has a long history of staying
out of civilian affairs, many see the military's role and power
growing dangerously as it is called on to defend democracy against
the rising rebel threat.
</P>
<P>
   In Peru, where President Alberto Fujimori last month won an
unprecedented third five-year term in elections widely denounced as
unfair, a once professional army has become increasingly answerable
to Fujimori's shadowy spy chief, Vladimiro Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   ''The case of Peru I think is illustrative of what is perhaps
the most difficult civilian-military dynamic that we have in Latin
America today,'' said David Scott Palmer, a Latin America
specialist at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups observing Peru's election accused soldiers
in the southern Ayacucho region of threatening peasants into voting
for Fujimori, whose power rests largely on a cozy relationship with
the army.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Andean region, military stirrings are most apparent
in Paraguay -- a struggling democracy that quelled a coup attempt
last month -- and in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   In Guatemala, where some 200,000 people died in a 36-year civil
war that ended in 1996, some military officers are still reluctant
to accept the inclusion of the left in the political process. And
there is continued tension in Nicaragua between an army controlled
by former Sandinista revolutionaries and the non-Sandinista
government.
</P>
<P>
   As Latin America's most troubled lands experience grumbling in
the barracks, some nations with improving economies are showing
real progress in taming once-restive generals. Among them are
Argentina, Chile, Brazil and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Chile's military made an extraordinary gesture of conciliation
last Tuesday when it promised to help determine the fate of more
than 1,000 dissidents who vanished after being arrested under the
dictatorship of Gen. Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine armed forces, discredited by a murderous 1976-83
dictatorship and a humiliating loss to Britain in the 1982
Falklands war, have also shown great deference to civilian rule in
recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
