<HEADLINE> Paraguay's Democracy Under Fire  </HEADLINE>
By BILL CORMIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- It was a throwback to South America's
military past: Tanks sped through the capital amid bursts of
chattering gunfire. Armed men crept in the shadows. A tank cannon
blasted a gaping hole in the pink facade of the Legislative Palace.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in four years, Paraguay's fragile democracy
was under fire -- a coup attempt by mutinous soldiers and police
bent on toppling current President Luis Gonzalo Macchi.
</P>
<P>
   But, threatened with air strikes by forces loyal to the
president, the renegade tank commanders fled on foot after just
four hours. The May 19 coup fizzled, and dozens were detained.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 11 years since the Paraguayan military toppled
dictator Alfredo Stroessner, whose 34-year reign was South
America's longest in the 20th century. The shaky democracy that
followed has hobbled from one crisis to another.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption is widespread, and poverty is worsening. Gasoline
prices are up, as are fares for public transportation and food
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Most Paraguayans view government leaders as ineffective and say
the unsettled conditions make the country vulnerable to political
infighting and coup plots.
</P>
<P>
   Walking amid rifle-toting soldiers during the state of emergency
imposed after the failed coup, Valeria Schussmuller, 21, talked of
her fears her country will never find its way out of the muddle
between dictatorship and democracy: ''Here we are in 2000 and this
is something out of the 1800s.''
</P>
<P>
   With per capita income just above $1,600 a year, some 22 percent
of Paraguay's 5.4 million people live in poverty. The unemployment
rate hovers near 16 percent. Some 300,000 peasants in the
countryside are clamoring for land and many people still depend on
cash-strapped state enterprises for their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   In eastern Paraguay, where half the population lives amid
rolling farm fields filled with corn, beans and cabbage, many are
desperate -- and fed up with the unkept promises of civilian
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''The peasants work practically for free these days. No
government helps us,'' said Sitto Cabrera, stopping his oxcart
outside Caaguazu, a city 100 miles east of Asuncion. He said he
barely makes ends meet ferrying corn and beans to market.
</P>
<P>
   Some even speak wistfully of the Stroessner days, like cabbage
farmer Efraim Espinola, sitting in his one-story wooden home,
chickens clucking out back on his 3&AMP;frac12; acres.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am 56 years old and in the Stroessner years we never heard
all this talk of corruption,'' he said. ''Under Stroessner we lived
better. I raised 10 children and always had money in my pocket
after I sold my produce. That would be impossible now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-18-00 1250 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000618.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats say divisions are behind them in key House race  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Call it a political marriage of convenience.
Maryanne Connelly, a candidate for a key seat in the House, and the
Democratic establishment that endorsed her opponent in the June 6
primary say they have made up and are united for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly's paper-thin victory over Union County Manager Michael
Lapolla gave her a starring role in the Democratic Party's strategy
to take back the House - even though she was not originally part of
the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leaders of Union County and leading state
Democrats including U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli had lined up behind
Lapolla. And in an unusual move, the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee - the election arm of House Democrats - jumped
into the primary and also backed Lapolla.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very disappointed that they got involved in a primary
and felt they should have stayed out of it,'' Connelly said last
week. ''But that's in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   DCCC spokesman Erik Smith said his group was attracted to
Lapolla because of his strong fund raising and because he had the
backing of key Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''What Maryanne Connelly accomplished was
extraordinary. I mean, overcoming the party support and (favored)
ballot position that Mike Lapolla had says a lot more about the
strength of her candidacy than anything else. She certainly
exceeded everyone's expectations. We give her credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee called Lapolla's
defeat ''embarrassing'' for its counterpart group, the DCCC, and
predicted the Democrats would suffer from ''a bitterly divided
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapolla conceded the 7th congressional district contest last
Monday, six days after the election, once the state had certified
the results. Connelly's margin of victory was 295 votes, less than
1 percent of the 32,850 votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Lapolla congratulated Connelly and pledged to
work for a Democratic victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, there was no love lost among Democrats.
Connelly took umbrage at a Lapolla radio ad portraying her as
flighty and indecisive, enlisting women's groups to call the ad
sexist. And Connelly accused prominent New Jersey Democrats of
pressuring her to leave the race.
</P>
<P>
   But Connelly said last week she is looking to the future, not
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, too, had a divisive primary in the 7th district,
especially over the involvement of a mysterious outside group that
ran attack ads seemingly designed to help the Republican who ended
up winning, Mike Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   One of the candidates targeted by ''Council for Responsible
Government,'' Assemblyman Joel Weingarten, spoke of ''rumors run
rampant'' that Ferguson campaign consultants were involved with the
group, something Ferguson has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate, Patrick Morrisey, criticized Ferguson for
''sleazy campaign tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kean Jr., who came in second behind Ferguson, filed a
complaint with the Federal Election Commission against the Council
for Responsible Government, saying the group acted like a political
action committee rather than a nonprofit group because it
''specifically advocated my defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said last week he is confident he has the support of
all three of his vanquished rivals. Kean noted the complaint he
filed has ''nothing to do with Mike'' and he pledged his support
for Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   ''I imagine from what I've heard that they're having a tougher
time unifying the party on their side than on our side,'' Ferguson
said in an interview. ''We're having everybody come together very
nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   The Connelly-Ferguson race is already under a national spotlight
because they are competing for an open seat in a competitive
district. The seat became open when Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley
Heights, decided to run for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   They offer clear distinctions on some major issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, an education consultant, favors experiments with
school vouchers, opposes abortion and would consider diverting a
portion of Social Security payroll taxes to privately-run accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly, the former mayor of Fanwood, opposes school vouchers,
supports abortion rights and opposes any steps toward privatizing
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson also said his general campaign will include a
gun-control component at odds with many in his party. He said he
supports universal registration and licensing of ''all guns'' and
will detail his proposal later in the campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
