<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minerals Bring Little to S. Leone  </HEADLINE>
By TIM SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Every day, men carrying tiny
stones walk into unmarked offices across this city of crumbling
concrete buildings and rotting clapboard homes. A safe often squats
in one corner of the room, and a small electronic scale sits on the
desk.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple transaction, a diamond exchanged for a wad of
bills, yet it's the grease that keeps the wreckage of this West
African nation's economy grinding along.
</P>
<P>
   More crucially, the enormous wealth buried in the dirt is the
fuel driving a horrific civil war that has killed and maimed tens
of thousands of innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Diamonds have been a curse, really,'' Christopher Johns, a
longtime Freetown diamond valuer and consultant, said as a teen-age
militiaman toting a rocket launcher patrolled Johns' street.
''Instead of being a blessing, they're a curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that curse can be seen nearly everywhere in Sierra
Leone, from its long history of coups to the mosquito-ridden mining
camps where diggers living on $1 a day and a handful of rice shovel
and sift for their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you nearly starve and sometimes things are better,''
said John Mariba, who at 45 has spent a third of his life working
the diamond-laced silt near the southern town of Bo, the main
diamond-producing region still in government hands.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly the curse can be seen in the effects of its eight-year
war: in hundreds of villages burned to the ground, in Freetown
neighborhoods reduced to rubble, in refugee camps filled with
civilians whose limbs were hacked off in rebel terror campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Diamonds are what have been fueling the war machine,'' said
Foreign Minister Sama Banya. ''The profits have all been going out
of the country while the rebels have been using the money to fuel
their atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamond-financed conflicts are nothing new in Africa. Angola's
decades-old civil war has been powered by its gems, which allow the
UNITA rebel movement to evade an international arms embargo. Congo
is moving toward the second anniversary of its own civil war, a
fight where many of the players -- the government, the rebels and
the foreign armies fighting for both sides -- are deeply involved in
the diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''Diamonds are a guerrilla's best friend,'' said Paul Collier,
author of a new World Bank study on the role of diamonds and other
commodities in financing conflict. ''Rebel groups need to meet a
payroll without producing anything, so they prey on an economic
activity that won't collapse under the weight of their predatory
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Nourished by Sierra Leone's mineral wealth, the rebel
Revolutionary United Front has seized nearly half the country
despite having almost no popular support. In May, less than a year
after a peace accord was signed, fighting flared again, triggered
in part by the decision of U.N. peacekeepers to move into
rebel-held diamond areas.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have been propped up for years by Charles Taylor, the
warlord who became president of neighboring Liberia, diplomats and
international observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone is far richer in diamonds than Liberia, yet Liberia
exported almost $300 million worth of the gems last year, compared
to barely $30 million for Sierra Leone, according to the Diamonds
High Council in Antwerp, Belgium. Many of Liberia's diamonds came
from rebel-controlled Sierra Leone, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds have become increasingly important in keeping what
remains of the economy afloat. Even the gems that are smuggled out
-- officials say more than three-quarters leave the country that way
-- are part of an informal hard currency that allows the country to
import food, fuel and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
   Few dealers take much notice of whether the diamonds they trade
come from government areas or rebel-held regions, which produce the
vast majority of the country's gems.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know,'' said one underground dealer, who asked to be
identified only as Mohammed. He snorted at the idea that he would
care.
</P>
<P>
   ''This one comes from rebels, this one from government mines,''
he said sarcastically in his dingy office, waving at a pair of
small stones on his desk. Outside his door, nearly a dozen men
waited to sell him more gems.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the outside world has begun paying attention
to the role of diamonds in Africa's wars. The United Nations is
investigating, and numerous countries are looking at ways to curb
the trade in gems from conflict areas.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone's former colonial ruler, Britain, formally proposed
in early June that an embargo be imposed on the sale of the
country's diamonds. The embargo would make it illegal to buy Sierra
Leonean diamonds, except those with a certificate of origin from
the government.
</P>
<P>
   The diamond exchange in Israel, a major center for expert
cutting and polishing of medium and large gems, announced Wednesday
that it would expel any member who deals in diamonds mined in war
zones.
</P>
<P>
   ''We as the Israeli diamond industry, as part of the
international diamond trade, are not prepared to lend a hand to
subsidizing these wars,'' said Shmuel Schnitzer, head of the
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Among Freetown's dealers, few believe a certification plan would
work. The enormous profits that can be made from diamonds mean
there are plenty of people willing to break the rules, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed, the Sierra Leonean dealer, produces a pair of uncut
stones from a slip of paper.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes people crazy, always talking 'diamond, diamond,
diamond, diamond,''' he said, smiling. ''That is money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
