<DOCNO> APW20000618.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: schools, governments flouting public records law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLEASANTVILLE, N.J. (AP) - Municipal governments and school
boards in southern New Jersey are routinely flouting New Jersey's
public records law by failing to release minutes of private
meetings, or keeping such poor notes it was impossible to explain
the need for secrecy in the first place, according to a newspaper
report.
</P>
<P>
   The Press of Atlantic City reported in Sunday's editions that 10
school boards or local governments were unwilling or unable to
produce minutes of their closed-session meetings, while another 33
provided minutes with so little detail that it was impossible to
know what was being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   State law permits schools and local governments to discuss
certain topics in secrecy, such as litigation and personnel
matters. But it also requires them to keep minutes of those
discussions and release them to the public once the need for
secrecy no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until we know for sure what is going on, there's no way of
knowing that everything is aboveboard,'' said Harry Pozycki,
chairman of the New Jersey chapter of Common Cause, a citizen
watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that some public bodies take a year or
more to release closed-session minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including the city of Ocean City and the school board in
Galloway Township, refuse to release anything from a closed session
meeting if one issue from that meeting is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   From reading meeting minutes, Ocean City taxpayers would never
know that it cost them $24,000 to settle a lawsuit against the
school board brought by a guidance counselor who claimed he wasn't
hired because he's white.
</P>
<P>
   The minutes of the April 22, 1998, meeting at which the
settlement was approved refer only to ''litigation,'' and a
''settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that the Avalon Board of Education has
not kept minutes of closed-session meetings since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general ruled in 1998 that closed-session
minutes must contain enough detail for the public to understand
''the reasonableness'' of actions taken by a public agency.
</P>
<P>
   That opinion was based on a state Supreme Court decision that
allowed The Press of Atlantic City access to closed-session minutes
concerning the resignation of the executive director of the
Atlantic City Expressway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
