<DOCNO> APW20000618.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Delays U.N. on Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With Lebanon insisting that Israel still
occupies part of its territory, Russia was delaying a formal
Security Council endorsement Sunday of the U.N. verification of
Israel's pullout from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The council reached tentative agreement on an endorsement
Saturday night after a marathon 10-hour session that included a
conference call with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, diplomats said Russia -- which has close ties to Syria,
the main power in Lebanon -- was under instructions to reject any
text that did not satisfy the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
   When a formal open council meeting started Sunday morning to
endorse the U.N. verification, Russia's senior counselor Vladimir
Sergeev asked for closed-door consultations, saying there were some
issues that still needed clarification.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's deputy ambassador Stewart Eldon expressed hope that
the formal meeting would be able to resume extremely quickly,
saying ''the matter is urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan is in the Middle East, heading
for Beirut on Monday, and wants the Security Council endorsement so
he can start discussing the next steps toward peace in Lebanon.
These include deploying U.N. peacekeepers and -- most critically --
the Lebanese army to southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Sunday, Lahoud called press reports that Lebanon
had accepted the U.N. certification as ''totally untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Lebanon insisted that it will not give its consent before the
(Israeli) withdrawal is first verified by its team and the U.N.
team,'' the statement added.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Lebanese and U.N. cartographers set out on foot to
inspect some of the disputed points.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss rejected the U.N.
verification of Israel's pullout shortly after Annan announced
Friday that Israel had completely withdrawn from Lebanon. Hoss
repeated his rejection on Saturday, saying Lebanon ''insists on
recovering every inch of its territory.''
</P>
<P>
   A Security Council endorsement of Israel's withdrawal would put
its political weight behind the United Nations' position, rather
than Lebanon's.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on northern Israel
from 1985 until its withdrawal on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Under 1978 Security Council resolutions, U.N. peacekeeping
troops were charged with verifying any Israeli pullout. They are
then charged with helping the Lebanese army restore security and
authority in the border zone.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's deputy U.N. ambassador, Michel Duval, said the U.N.
peacekeeping force in Lebanon had rechecked five or six positions
and installations Saturday that the Lebanese government raised
questions about ''and has confirmed the withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations wants the Lebanese army deployed to the south
as quickly as possible because Shiite Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas,
who fought the Israeli troops for years, have moved into the former
occupied zone and taken de facto control.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla presence in the zone right across from Israel's
border is especially a concern for residents of northern Israeli
towns, who fear guerrilla attacks. On Saturday, Hezbollah warned it
would resume attacks on Israel's north if the Jewish state does not
give up tracts of land claimed by Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''All violations should be dealt with ... otherwise we consider
the mission of liberating Lebanese territory to be incomplete and
resistance remains our choice to liberate the last inch of our
occupied land,'' Hezbollah said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's office welcomed Annan's
declaration, saying in a statement Saturday that it expected the
United Nations to act to ''help restore law and order in the
area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
