<HEADLINE> Md. Man Charged With Killing Priest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) -- A Maryland laborer with a history of
burglary arrests was charged with beating and stabbing to death a
priest who surprised an intruder in the rectory of his church.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Robert Paul Lucas, 25, on a charge of
first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're excited, proud to have this case closed, but on the
other hand we remain very sad,'' Chief Charles Moose of the
Montgomery County Police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe Lucas attacked Monsignor Thomas M. Wells, 56,
after Wells caught him June 8 burglarizing the rectory, where the
priest lived, next to Mother Seton Catholic Church in Germantown,
Md., a suburb of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they are building a strong case against Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a confession from the perpetrator as well as
scientific and forensic evidence,'' said the county's state's
attorney, Douglas Gansler.
</P>
<P>
   He said police found items from the rectory in Lucas'
possession. A boot Lucas was wearing matched a print found at the
murder scene, Gansler said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a lawyer called his office Thursday and informed
prosecutors that a former client had named Lucas as the priest's
killer. Police followed and watched Lucas, then arrested him
Saturday in the van where he lived.
</P>
