<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Sign Accord  </HEADLINE>
By HASSANE MEFTAHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Ethiopia and Eritrea agreed Sunday to
cease hostilities immediately in their 2-year-old border war that
has killed, wounded and displaced multitudes, signaling a new
African mission for U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The accord, signed after weeks of tense negotiations in the
Algerian capital punctuated by fighting at home in the Horn of
Africa, opens the way to a definitive peace, allowing for a
reprieve while negotiators delineate the bitterly disputed
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia is to redeploy troops inside Eritrea, its much smaller
neighbor, and an international peacekeeping mission is to patrol a
buffer zone on Eritrean territory between the combatants.
</P>
<P>
   ''This accord marks the beginning of the end of two years of
conflict,'' Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile Eritrean Foreign
Minister Haile Woldansae said. It is ''the first concrete step
toward peace between the two countries after a useless war.''
</P>
<P>
   Woldansae and his Ethiopian counterpart, Seyoum Mesfin, shook
hands after signing the agreement, reached under the auspices of
the Organization of African Unity, currently headed by Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   The ''cessation of hostilities'' accord falls short of a full,
unconditional cease-fire, which would place severe limits even on
acting in self defense and carry stiff sanctions for any violation.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia has all along reserved the right to respond to any
Eritrean provocations under a cessation of hostilities agreement,
which places no limits on responding to low-level harassing fire
that often takes place along the front lines even after an
agreement is signed.
</P>
<P>
   ''My hope is that the adverse party respects the accord,'' said
Mesfin, the Ethiopian foreign minister. He vowed to ''fully take
part in the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton called the accord a
''breakthrough which ... can and should permit these two countries
to realize their potential in peace, instead of squandering it in
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's special envoy Anthony Lake was present at the signing,
along with OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim and EU
representative Rino Seri of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 15-point agreement, the two countries ''will cease all
hostile activity on land and in the air immediately after the
signature of the accord, guarantee freedom of movement and access
to the peacekeeping mission and the respect for and protection of
the members of this mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord calls for Ethiopia to redeploy its troops in the two
weeks following the peacekeepers' deployment. However, it set no
date for the start of the peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia is to redeploy troops from positions captured after
Feb. 6, 1999, the start of a major offensive, and from
''territories not under its administration before May 6, 1998'' --
the start of the war over the 620 mile border.
</P>
<P>
   However, the accord said ''the redeployment of Ethiopian forces
will not prejudge the final status of contested territories'' -- an
apparent reference to Ethiopia's contention that changes on the
ground should be reflected in a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika called the agreement ''a
source of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   With it, ''Africa has the right to believe in the possibility of
resolving in the same peaceful manner other complex tragedies still
shaking'' the continent, Bouteflika said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Friday dispatched a team of
experts to Algiers to discuss the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats have suggested a force of 2,000 troops, but
others have said nearly double that may be required. U.N.
peacekeepers already are deployed in places like Sierra Leone and
East Timor with a planned Congo mission.
</P>
<P>
   The war has left tens of thousands of people dead and displaced
tens of thousands of Eritreans, with some 80,000 fleeing to Sudan.
The economic costs are equally steep. Military analysts say the two
impoverished countries have spent more than $1 billion on arms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-18-00 1353 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000618.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-18 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Streeters find boxing is new adrenalin rush  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Every month, well-dressed men like John Oden
leave their climate-controlled offices on Wall Street for a short
limo ride to a lonely Brooklyn warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing suspicious here - they're just searching for new
ways to beat someone at yet another game.
</P>
<P>
   They climb winding concrete stairs and emerge into a cavernous
room. Shouting voices blend with the sounds of fists striking
bodies and punching bags, and the air is thick with sweat. They
peal off silk ties, starched shirts and pressed pants, and change
into nylon shirts and shorts. Assistants tape their hands, strap on
14-ounce or 16-ounce gloves the color of fresh-spilled blood and
attach their headgear.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they slip under a thick rope, and a bell announces it's
''White Collar Sparring Night.'' These men and a growing number of
women, some who compete for deals worth millions or billions in
their day jobs, have found a new form of combat at historic
Gleason's Gym.
</P>
<P>
   ''Boxing is the ultimate sport: It's one-on-one, a mano-a-mano
face off,'' said Oden, a money manager for a billion-dollar firm
who refused to give his age, saying only that he is in his 50s.
''When I am in the ring, I am not even remotely thinking of what
went on in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Oden, a transplanted Texan with the twang to match, took up
boxing eight years ago when jogging and tennis became boring and
the 6-foot-4 executive noticed his stomach beginning to bulge.
Almost instantly, he fell in love with the exhilaration of hitting
- and the anxiety of being hit.
</P>
<P>
   For about a decade, a handful of places like Gleason's have
opened their doors to investment bankers, real estate developers,
doctors, even a New York state judge. Most are people with money to
burn and egos to be stoked.
</P>
<P>
   Gleason's was perfect. The gym opened in 1937 in the Bronx, then
moved to midtown Manhattan before crossing the river to its present
setting in a nondescript warehouse under the Brooklyn Bridge. Jake
LaMotta, Muhammad Ali, and Mike Tyson are just a few of the greats
to break a sweat there.
</P>
<P>
   About 850 fighters now work out at Gleason's, and it still has
its seasoned pros like IBF welterweight champ Zab ''Super'' Judah.
There's a cache of retired fighters, such as Edwin Viruet, who
twice took famed KO artist Roberto Duran the distance, and Olympic
boxer Nikos Michalis Spanakos, who roomed with Ali, then named
Cassius Clay, at the 1960 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Bruce Silverglade said the white-collar ''professionals''
are welcomed, even encouraged by the ring pros. In boxing, people
say, fighters share a common trait: Terror.
</P>
<P>
   ''They all go in there with fear,'' Silverglade said. ''There's
not a professional who won't go in their without some level of
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Prefight jitters aren't like the butterflies of other sports.
Oden recalled hyperventilating in his first fight. Some with years
of experience admit still having anxious starts. In most cases,
fear dissipates after the first blow. Not just a glancing shot,
though; it needs a solid shot to the nose - the kind that leaves an
unpleasant flavor in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ''It becomes fun once you get over that hump,'' said Charlie
Miller, an artist and writer. ''I don't like getting hit, but it
teaches you things.''
</P>
<P>
   On this night, there is all sorts of hitting between Oden and
his opponent, Mark Settembre. Three weeks earlier at another gym,
they were paired in Settembre's first bout. Oden won, and the
48-year-old Settembre trained hard for the rematch because his neck
was stiff for three days - and he wanted some payback.
</P>
<P>
   Settembre, a real estate developer, listened attentively to Tom
Patti, his friend and trainer. Like a majority of the white-collar
fighters, Settembre works outs several times a week, punching bags
until his arms ache and his legs wobble.
</P>
<P>
   Patti, who befriended Mike Tyson at a reform school years ago
and recently trained the disturbed champion for about a year, told
Settembre to duck Oden's left jab and counter with a stiff left.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, and at times awkwardly, the two fighters came at
each other with angry fists. When the bell rang after the third and
final two-minute round, both fighters hugged and held up trophies.
That's right, there's two winners at Gleason's. The gym doesn't
have judges - the $20 entry fee essentially covers the cost of the
gold-tinted keepsake.
</P>
<P>
   ''I abandoned (judging) because it's supposed to be a fun
event,'' Silverglade said. ''When there were winners and losers,
there were zillionaires from Wall Street who would lose and go home
and be really upset about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem strange that Settembre has a trainer, but given
the bank accounts of many of these guys, it only makes sense. So
does the plan to take a handful to London in July, where they will
fight rich British boxers.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone who fights is loaded. Take Tony Pellegrino, a
58-year-old electrician who took up the sport ''because boxing is
in my blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My father was a contend-ah,'' Pellegrino said. ''He taught me
when I was a little kid, but he never wanted me to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Pellegrino began boxing 15 years ago. He fights a dozen times
per year, much to the chagrin of his wife, Carmel, who sits
ringside with 30 or 40 other fans for every bout.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he first told me, I said, 'No, you're crazy, what are you
thinking about?''' she said, grimacing when her husband took a
punch to the gut. ''But he was always a man who worked very hard,
He never did anything for himself and he's made a lot of friends
doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pellegrino could have sustained a severe injury from his
opponent, 34-year-old financial analyst Edwin Calderon. The
younger, stronger and more dexterous Calderon started the fight
with a flurry of punches, but slowed and lessened their effect
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It was an example of most fights. While a few get out of hand,
forcing a referee to step in before anyone gets mauled, most of the
fighters know each other. The gym creates a sense of community, and
civility.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just do it to get in shape,'' said Calderon. ''I don't
intend to hurt anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, boxers can get hurt. Broken noses or jaws are always
possibilities, despite the presence of headgear. But the protective
gear generally prevents the face from bruising, and dress shirts
cover up body bruises. A hefty bank roll goes a long way, too, in
easing pain with massage and physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Along with not being rich, not all the fighters are male either.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Mendola just made her debut and complained it had been
against a man. ''I would have liked to have fought a girl,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mendola, who as a Long Island nurse usually helps people,
not hurts them, then added: ''I'm coming back for the next one,
though. It's great - it's like a rush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
