<HEADLINE> Blige Wows Crowd at Radio City  </HEADLINE>
By NEKESA MUMBI MOODY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- As she opened her three-concert stand at Radio
City Music Hall, Mary J. Blige insisted she was ''just plain' old
Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a little hard to grasp given her glammed-up attire, a
rhinestone bra and hip-hugging pants that showed off her toned
body.
</P>
<P>
   But what made the line from her hit ''Deep Inside'' even more
hard to believe was her dynamic performance, in which she not only
lived up to her moniker as the Queen of Hip-Hop Soul but proved
herself unique in today's R&AMP;B world: a gritty performer who not
only duplicates the vocals on her albums, but greatly exceeds them.
</P>
<P>
   Blige improvised on just about every song, even sounding a
little like a skilled jazz singer as she scatted and freestyled on
numbers like ''All That I Can Say.'' Her voice had its typical
scratchy edge, yet at the same time sounded sweet and enticing.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's sold-out concert, one of the first in her nationwide
summer tour, proved to be a homecoming of sorts for Blige, a
Yonkers, N.Y., native, and the adoring crowding showered her with
love as if she was a long-lost relative. They cheered, sang along
with just about every song, and chanted ''Go Mary, Go Mary,'' as
Blige strolled across the stage like a B-boy rapper.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Blige showed no signs of fatigue as she gyrated while
singing earlier hits like ''Mary Jane (All Night Long),'' and
''Love No Limit.'' She took only a brief respite, leaving the stage
to showcase her four male backup dancers after rapping with Grand
Pupa of Brand Nubian fame on ''What's the 411,'' the title track of
her first album.
</P>
<P>
   She returned in a new outfit -- and wig, changing to blond from
an auburn feather style she had worn at the beginning of the
concert. Her vocal stylings, however, remained the same while she
brought the tempo down to sing some heartfelt ballads. The crowd
was so into the concert at that point that she barely sang ''I'm
Goin' Down,'' letting the ladies in the audience sing much of the
song's lyrics as she shook her head in awe of the crowd
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Blige really brought the house down when she sang songs about
betrayal and hurt, like with ''Your Child,'' about a man who cheats
and has a child with another woman. She sang with all the
appropriate drama, holding her head in her hands, shooting
accusatory glances at the audience and shaking her finger while
singing angrily, ''She said it's your child!'' By the time Blige
finished the set, she was doling out advice to the women in the
audience, urging them to bolt a bad relationship: ''You don't have
to take that,'' she told them, recalling some of her own pain.
</P>
<P>
   But she made sure to go out on a high note, a disco-flavored
''Let No Man Put Asunder'' and the dreamy ''Everything'' as an
encore, during which she professed her love for audience. And at
that point, it was clear the feeling was mutual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
