<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile Deployment Goal in Doubt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Problems with a booster rocket and other
elements of a national missile defense system seriously threaten
the project's 2005 deployment target date, a Pentagon panel
reportedly has advised Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have been saying privately for months that
the target date, already postponed from 2003, is overly ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   The latest confidential study, reported Sunday by The Washington
Post, warns of a ''substantial schedule risk, but not particularly
high technical risk,'' of a fundamental engineering or scientific
flaw in the system, which is now being tested.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quotes an unidentified senior officer familiar
with the report as saying, ''It is like remodeling a kitchen: It
may not get done by (the date the builder promised), but it will
get done.''
</P>
<P>
   As visualized by Clinton administration planners, the system of
targeting radars, interceptor missiles and high-speed computers
would have 120 missiles in place by 2007 to protect all 50 states
against primitive missiles fired by countries newly armed with
nuclear and missile technology. North Korea or Iran are often
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, headed by retired Gen. Larry Welch, former chief of
staff for the Air Force, gave missile defense developers a ''B-plus
grade for work done thus far'' but reported one apparent shortfall
not previously public.
</P>
<P>
   ''The report notes engineering problems in the construction of
the high-speed interceptor missile that is supposed to boost the
kill vehicle into space,'' the Post quoted an official as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ''Initial testing of the booster has been delayed repeatedly
this year and is now scheduled for September, and yet it is
supposed to be ready for a flight test of the entire system by
early next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Interceptor tests so far have had patchy results. The next
interception is scheduled for July 7. The panel of prominent
scientists and former top defense officials said that test is vital
to the program's next step, President Clinton's decision this fall
whether to start construction.
</P>
<P>
   ''If all goes perfectly or, on the contrary, if the test is a
complete disaster, the Pentagon should be able to present Clinton
with a clear judgment on the status of the system,'' the Post said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But in the more likely event that some elements of the system
work well and others encounter problems, Pentagon analysts may not
be able to evaluate the test data in time.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Ballistic Missile Defense Organization:
http://www.acq.osd.mil/bmdo/bmdolink/html/nmd.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
